  "text": "Skin represents the first-line defense of the human body against external stimuli. The innate immune system is the major contributor to acute inflammation induced by microbial infection and enables the skin to protect the host from infection. In the skin, nonprofessional immune cells, such as keratinocytes and sebocytes, significantly contribute to its innate immunity. Toll-like receptors (TLRs) are the most important pattern recognition receptors, which are responsible for sensing the presence of microorganisms. TLRs, with the exception of TLR3, accomplish their signals through the myeloid differentiation factor 88 (MyD88)-dependent pathway by activating nuclear factor-κB (NF-κB) and mitogen-activated protein kinases (MAPKs) and subsequently regulating cytokine gene expression [CITATION_1] .",
